#: ../manual/vitals/screenshots.rst:20
msgid ""
":kbd:`ctrl-F3` will take a screenshot of your Blender window and then open "
"the Blender :guilabel:`File Browser` window, allowing you to specify the "
"name and location of the screenshot. In the example image at the right, the "
"PNG format will be the output of the screenshot taken (settings are the same"
" as the ones available to save render results). When the Blender "
":guilabel:`File Browser` window opens for you, at the left, there is a tab "
"called *Save Screenshot* where you can find format settings and a checkbox "
"with the option *Full Screen*."
msgstr ""

#: ../manual/vitals/screenshots.rst:28
msgid ""
"Check the Option to save the entire Blender window (full width and height of"
" the Blender window you are using when you call the command)."
msgstr ""

#: ../manual/vitals/screenshots.rst:30
msgid ""
"Uncheck the box to save only your active window (where your mouse is located"
" when you call the command)."
msgstr ""

#: ../manual/vitals/screenshots.rst:35
msgid "Search Functionality"
msgstr ""

#: ../manual/vitals/screenshots.rst:37
msgid "Keyboard Shortcut Conflicts"
msgstr ""

#: ../manual/vitals/screenshots.rst:39
msgid ""
"Sometimes, the operating System you are using is designed to use some "
"Shortcuts that the default Blender installation also uses for its functions."
" In this case, you can use the search functionality present in Blender. (See"
" Fig: Search Functionality). Hit :kbd:`space` and type "
":guilabel:`Screenshot`, in the Search Popup."
msgstr ""

#: ../manual/vitals/screenshots.rst:46
msgid "Operating System Screenshots"
msgstr ""

#: ../manual/vitals/screenshots.rst:48
msgid ""
"You may also use the Operating system to capture the screen to the "
"clipboard. You can then paste the image from the clipboard into your image "
"editor."
msgstr ""

#: ../manual/vitals/screenshots.rst:53
msgid "Windows Screenshots"
msgstr ""

#: ../manual/vitals/screenshots.rst:55
msgid ""
"Press :kbd:`Alt-Print Screen` to capture the active program window to the "
"clipboard."
msgstr ""

#: ../manual/vitals/screenshots.rst:59
msgid "Mac OSX Screenshots"
msgstr ""

#: ../manual/vitals/screenshots.rst:61
msgid ""
"Press :kbd:`cmd-shift-3` to capture the screen to a file on the desktop."
msgstr ""

#: ../manual/vitals/screenshots.rst:63
msgid "Press :kbd:`ctrl-cmd-shift-3` to capture the screen to the clipboard."
msgstr ""

#: ../manual/vitals/screenshots.rst:65
msgid ""
"Press :kbd:`cmd-shift-4` to capture an area of the screen to a file on the "
"desktop."
msgstr ""

#: ../manual/vitals/screenshots.rst:67
msgid ""
"Press :kbd:`ctrl-cmd-shift-4` to capture an area of the screen to the "
"clipboard."
msgstr ""

#: ../manual/vitals/screenshots.rst:71
msgid "GNU/Linux Screenshots"
msgstr ""

#: ../manual/vitals/screenshots.rst:73
msgid ""
"On some Linux distributions (such as Ubuntu) and window managers, you can "
"press :kbd:`Print Screen` to capture the screen to a file. For other "
"distributions or window managers you may require additional software. "
"Examples of such software include, but are not limited to: `xvidcap "
"<http://xvidcap.sourceforge.net/>`__, `scrot "
"<http://freshmeat.net/projects/scrot/>`__ and `recordMyDesktop "
"<http://recordmydesktop.sourceforge.net/about.php>`__. Consult your "
"distribution's manual or software repository for more information."
msgstr ""

